n pharmaceutical industry and forever altering the course of medicine. Drawing on a wealth of previously unused archival material, Medical Monopoly combines legal, medical, and business history to offer a sweeping new interpretation of the origins of the complex and often troubling relationship between the pharmaceutical industry and medical practice today. Joseph M. Gabriel provides the first detailed history of patent and trademark law as it relates to the nineteenth-century pharmaceutical industry as well as a unique interpretation of medical ethics, therapeutic reform, and the efforts to regulate the market in pharmaceuticals before World War I. His book will be of interest not only to historians of medicine and science and intellectual property scholars but also to anyone following contemporary debates about the pharmaceutical industry, the patenting of scientific discoveries, and the role of advertising in the marketplace.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aMEDICAL / General.2bisacsh  aintellectual property, patents, medical research, monopoly, pharmaceutical industry, medicine, healthcare, trademarks, drug manufacturers, physicians, doctors, civil war, scientific ethics, prescription drugs, therapeutic reform, capitalism, markets, commercialism, big pharma, law, legislation, advertising, nonfiction, legal system, history, politics, regulation, science, treatment, cure, palliative care, development.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022610818640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226108216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226108216/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles